I should mention that maybe it's a bit premature to generalise everything away from `NNReal`. Certainly for now merely following the `Nat.floor` API (but specialising `Œ± := ENNReal` everywhere) is plenty fine.
Should it take values in `ENat`?

@YaelDillies made the same remark when I mentioned this. My eventual use case would coerce back to `ENNReal` anyway, but I think you have a good point and the floor function might be more naturally be defined as `ENat` valued.

I modified the PR accordingly, except I only made the necessary `ENat` topology instance very quickly in this file locally and `sorry`ed out the proof that it is the order topology. If this approach looks otherwise acceptable, I could see if I can fill in the necessary parts about `ENat` topology.
I would tend to think this should be called `ENat.floor` to match `Nat.floor` and `Int.floor`. Other types it could apply to are `ENNRat` (doesn't exist yet), `EReal`, `ERat`

Yes, that and mimicking the API of `Nat.floor` makes sense now if this is made `ENat`-valued. (The topology on `ENat` is my main concern with this currently. And to a smaller extent the convenience of the required casts back to `ENNReal`, since there does not seem to be a lot of API for `ENat`, and `ENNReal` by itself can already be less-than-pleasant to work with at times.)

I originally thought the `ENNReal.floor` would be a one-off and therefore different from the more standard floor designs, but maybe someone can some day have use for a floor function on the `ENNRat`, too.

I will try to make this more parallel to the existing one. Thanks for the comment and the improvements to code!
The good thing about making your function be `ENat`-valued is that it suddenly forms a Galois coinsertion: `GaloisCoinsertion ENat.toENNReal ENat.floor` should hold.

```suggestion
@[gcongr] lemma floor_mono (h : x ‚â§ y) : x.floor ‚â§ y.floor := sSup_le_sSup <| fun _ hx ‚Ü¶ hx.trans h
```
Maybe worth turning around and simping

This I am slightly unsure of. My concern is because `ENNReal`s can be complicated to work with, and to prove things about them, one still very often breaks to cases and handles the finite case by casting to `NNReal`. That is more or less how this lemma is used already below. But perhaps since it certainly cannot be a simp lemma this way, one would anyway be expected to rewrite backwards in such cases. So perhaps I will try and see at least the first effects.

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma floor_zero : floor 0 = 0 := by exact_mod_cast ENNReal.floor_coe_eq 0
```

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma floor_one : floor 1 = 1 := by exact_mod_cast ENNReal.floor_coe_eq 1
```

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma floor_top : floor ‚àû = ‚ä§ := floor_coe_eq ‚ä§
```

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma floor_coe (n : ‚Ñï‚àû) :
```
Can you try following the `Nat.floor` API? This involves proving `floor_add_nat` (maybe renamed to `floor_add_natCast` before `floor_add_one`

```suggestion
* `‚åäa‚åã‚Çë` is `ENat.floor a`.
```
for "extended" might be clearer?

```suggestion
lemma ENat.cast_natCast [Semiring Œ±] [Preorder Œ±] [CoeTC ‚Ñï‚àû Œ±] [CastNatENatClass Œ±] {n : ‚Ñï} :
```
